A078849.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes separated by 3 consecutive differences each <=6 (i.e., when d=2,4 or 6) and forming d-pattern=[2, 6,6]; short d-string notation of pattern = [266].
formula: Primes p = p(i) such that p(i+1)=p+2, p(i+2)=p+2+6, p(i+3)=p+2+6+6.

A078850.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes separated by 3 consecutive differences each <=6 (i.e., when d=2,4 or 6) and forming d-pattern=[4,2,6]; short d-string notation of pattern = [426].
formula: Primes p = p(i) such that p(i+1)=p+4, p(i+2)=p+4+2, p(i+3)=p+4+2+6.

A078851.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes separated by 3 consecutive differences each <=6 (i.e., when d=2,4 or 6) and forming d-pattern=[4, 6, 2]; short d-string notation of pattern = [462].
formula: Primes p = p(i) such that p(i+1)=p+4, p(i+2)=p+4+6, p(i+3)=p+4+6+2.

A078852.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes separated by 3 consecutive differences each <=6 (i.e., when d=2,4 or 6) and forming d-pattern=[4, 6,6]; short d-string notation of pattern = [466].
formula: Primes p = p(i) such that p(i+1)=p+4, p(i+2)=p+4+6, p(i+3)=p+4+6+6.

A078853.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes separated by 3 consecutive differences each <=6 (i.e., when d = 2, 4 or 6) and forming d-pattern=[6,2,4]; short d-string notation of pattern = [624].
formula: Primes p = p(i) such that p(i+1)=p+6, p(i+2)=p+6+2, p(i+3)=p+6+2+4.

A078854.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes separated by 3 consecutive differences each <=6 (i.e., when d=2,4 or 6) and forming d-pattern=[6, 2,6]; short d-string notation of pattern = [626].
formula: Primes p = p(i) such that p(i+1)=p+6, p(i+2)=p+6+2, p(i+3)=p+6+2+6.

A078855.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes separated by 3 consecutive differences each <=6 (i.e., when d=2,4 or 6) and forming d-pattern=[6, 4,2]; short d-string notation of pattern = [642].
formula: Primes p = p(i) such that p(i+1)=p+6, p(i+2)=p+6+4, p(i+3)=p+6+4+2.

A078856.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes whose consecutive differences have d-pattern = [6, 4, 6]; short d-string notation for pattern = [646].
formula: Primes p = p_(i) such that p_(i+1) = p + 6, p_(i+2) = p + 6 + 4, p_(i+3) = p + 6 + 4 + 6.

A078857.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes separated by 3 consecutive differences each <=6 (i.e., when d=2,4 or 6) and forming d-pattern=[6, 6,2]; short d-string notation of pattern = [662].
formula: Primes p = p(i) such that p(i+1)=p+6, p(i+2)=p+6+6, p(i+3)=p+6+6+2.

A078858.name: Initial term in sequence of four consecutive primes separated by 3 consecutive differences each <=6 (i.e., when d = 2, 4 or 6) and forming d-pattern = [6, 6, 4]; short d-string notation of pattern = [664].

A078859.name: Least positive residues (mod 210) representing those residue classes which can be the lesser of twin prime pairs (A001359).
formula: Intersection[RRS(210), 2+RRS{210)]-2 and {3, 5}. RRS(210)=reduced residue system of 210=first 48=phi(210) terms of A008364; two additional term 3 and 5 are singular cases; 210k+r generates complete A001359 with suitable k and r taken from these 15+2 numbers.

A078860.name: Least positive residues [mod 210] representing those residue classes which can be lesser of prime pairs from A029710.
formula: Intersection[RRS(210), 4+RRS{210)]-4 and {7}. RRS[210]=reduced residue system of 210=first 48=phi[210] terms of A008364; additional term 7 is a singular cases; 210k+r generates complete A029710 with suitable k and r taken from these 15+1 numbers.

A078861.name: Least positive residues [mod 210] representing those residue classes which can be smaller prime of a difference 6 taken from A031924.
formula: Intersection[RRS(210), 6+RRS{210)]-6. RRS[210]=reduced residue system of 210=first 48=phi[210] terms of A008364; 210k+r generates complete A031924 with suitable k and r taken from these 30 numbers.

A078862.name: Smallest primes from A031924, each belonging to those different residue class of mod 210 which are listed in A078861. Arranged according to possible least positive residues mod 210.

A078863.name: Smallest primes from A029710, each belonging to those different residue class of mod 210 which are listed in A078860. Arranged according to possible least positive residues mod 210.

A078864.name: Smallest primes from A001359, each belonging to those different residue class of mod 210 which are listed in A078859. Arranged according to possible least positive residues mod 210.

A078865.name: Difference of consecutive primorial numbers divided by 4.

A078866.name: The quadruples (d1,d2,d3,d4) with elements in {2,4,6} are listed in lexicographic order; for each quadruple, this sequence lists the smallest prime p >= 5 such that the differences between the 5 consecutive primes starting with p are (d1,d2,d3,d4), if such a prime exists.

A078868.name: Decimal concatenations of the quadruples (d1,d2,d3,d4) with elements in {2,4,6} for which there exists a prime p >= 5 such that the differences between the 5 consecutive primes starting with p are (d1,d2,d3,d4).

A078869.name: Number of n-tuples with elements in {2,4,6} which can occur as the differences between n+1 consecutive primes > n+1. (Values of a(11), ..., a(18) are conjectured to be correct, but are only known to be upper bounds.)

A078870.name: Decimal concatenations of the 38 quintuples (d1,d2,d3,d4,d5) with elements in {2,4,6} for which there exists a prime p >= 7 such that the differences between the 6 consecutive primes starting with p are (d1,d2,d3,d4,d5).

A078871.name: Decimal concatenations of the 6-tuples (d1,d2,d3,d4,d5,d6) with elements in {2,4,6} for which there exists a prime p >= 7 such that the differences between the 7 consecutive primes starting with p are (d1,d2,d3,d4,d5,d6).

A078872.name: The quintuples (d1,d2,d3,d4,d5) with elements in {2,4,6} are listed in lexicographic order; for each quintuple, this sequence lists the smallest prime p >= 7 such that the differences between the 6 consecutive primes starting with p are (d1,d2,d3,d4,d5), if such a prime exists.

A078874.name: The 6-tuples (d1,d2,d3,d4,d5,d6) with elements in {2,4,6} are listed in lexicographic order; for each 6-tuple, this sequence lists the smallest prime p >= 7 such that the differences between the 7 consecutive primes starting with p are (d1,d2,d3,d4,d5,d6), if such a prime exists.

A078878.name: Irreducible polynomial coefficient of singular value associated with sqrt(2n).

A078879.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = ceiling(k^2 / n), 0 < k <= n.

A078880.name: The sequence starting with 2 that equals its own run length sequence.
formula: a(n) = k(n+1), where k=A000002, the Kolakoski sequence.

A078881.name: Size of the largest subset S of {1,2,3,...,n} with the property that if i and j are distinct elements of S then i XOR j is not in S, where XOR is the bitwise exclusive-OR operator.

A078882.name: Number of subsets S of {1,2,3,...,n} with the largest possible cardinality consistent with the requirement that if i and j are distinct elements of S then i XOR j is not in S. XOR is the bitwise exclusive-OR operator.

A078883.name: Lesser member p of a twin prime pair such that p+1 is 3-smooth.

A078884.name: Greater member p of a twin prime pair such that p-1 is 3-smooth.

A078885.name: Decimal expansion of Sum {n>=0} 1/3^(2^n).
formula: Equals -Sum_{k>=1} mu(2*k)/(3^k - 1), where mu is the Möbius function (A008683). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jul 12 2020

A078886.name: Decimal expansion of Sum {n>=0} 1/5^(2^n).
formula: Equals -Sum_{k>=1} mu(2*k)/(5^k - 1), where mu is the Möbius function (A008683). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jul 12 2020

A078887.name: Decimal expansion of Sum {n>=0} 1/6^(2^n).
formula: Equals -Sum_{k>=1} mu(2*k)/(6^k - 1), where mu is the Möbius function (A008683). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jul 12 2020

A078888.name: Decimal expansion of Sum {n>=0} 1/7^(2^n).
formula: Equals -Sum_{k>=1} mu(2*k)/(7^k - 1), where mu is the Möbius function (A008683). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jul 12 2020

A078889.name: Decimal expansion of Sum {n>=0} 1/8^(2^n).
formula: Equals -Sum_{k>=1} mu(2*k)/(8^k - 1), where mu is the Möbius function (A008683). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jul 12 2020

A078890.name: Decimal expansion of Sum {n>=0} 1/9^(2^n).
formula: Equals -Sum_{k>=1} mu(2*k)/(9^k - 1), where mu is the Möbius function (A008683). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jul 12 2020

A078891.name: Concatenate first n triangular numbers in reverse order.

A078892.name: Numbers n such that phi(n) - 1 is prime, where phi is Euler's totient function (A000010).

A078893.name: Composite numbers n such that phi(n) - 1 is prime, where phi is Euler's totient function (A000010).

A078894.name: Start with a list of all the primes and repeatedly add the first element A of the list to the sequence and strike off every A-th element of the list.

A078895.name: Palindromes which are a nontrivial product of 3 palindromes (which need not be distinct).

A078896.name: Number of times the smallest prime factor of n is a factor in all numbers <=n; a(1)=1.

A078897.name: Number of times the greatest prime factor of n is a factor in all numbers <=n; a(1)=1.

A078898.name: Number of times the smallest prime factor of n is the smallest prime factor for numbers <= n; a(0)=0, a(1)=1.
formula: Ordinal transform of A020639 (Lpf). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Aug 28 2006

[Instead of Moebius mu (A008683) one could use Liouville's lambda (A008836) in the above formulas, because all primorials (A002110) are squarefree. A020639(n) gives the smallest prime dividing n, and A055396 gives its index].

a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1, a(2n) = n, a(2n+1) = a(A250470(2n+1)). [After a similar recursive formula for A246277. However, this cannot be used for computing the sequence, unless a definition for A250470(n) is found which doesn't require computing the value of A078898(n).]
For n > 1: a(n)=1 if and only if n is prime.
a(n) = 2 if and only if n is a square of a prime.
For all n >= 1: a(A251728(n)) = A243055(A251728(n)) + 2. That is, if n is a semiprime of the form prime(i)*prime(j), prime(i) <= prime(j) < prime(i)^2, then a(n) = (j-i)+2.

A078899.name: Number of times the greatest prime factor of n is the greatest prime factor for numbers <=n; a(1)=1.
formula: Ordinal transform of A006530 (Gpf). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Aug 28 2006

A078900.name: Generalized Fermat numbers of the form (k+1)^2^m + k^2^m, with m>0.

A078901.name: Generalized Fermat numbers of the form (k+1)^2^m + k^2^m, with m>1.

A078902.name: Generalized Fermat primes of the form (k+1)^2^m + k^2^m, with m>1.

A078905.name: The q expansion of Lambda^5, a Hauptmodul for Gamma_1(5).
formula: G.f. A(x) = x * B(x)^5 where B(x) is the g.f. of A007325.
G.f. A(q) satisfies 0 = f(A(q), A(q^2)) where f(u,v) = u^2 - v + u*v^3 + u^3*v^2 + 10*u*v * (1 - u + v + u*v). - _Michael Somos_, Mar 09 2004
Given g.f. A(q), then q * A'(q) / A(q) = g.f. of A109064. [Duke (2005)] - _Michael Somos_, Jul 09 2014

A078906.name: Expansion of j in powers of Gamma(5)-modular function Lambda^5.

A078907.name: Expansion of modular function j/256 in powers of m=k^2=lambda(t).

A078908.name: Let r+i*s be the sum, with multiplicity, of the first-quadrant Gaussian primes dividing n; sequence gives r values (with a(1) = 0).

A078909.name: Let r+i*s be the sum, with multiplicity, of the first-quadrant Gaussian primes dividing n; sequence gives s values.

A078910.name: Let r+i*s be the sum of the distinct first-quadrant Gaussian integers dividing n; sequence gives r values.

A078911.name: Let r+i*s be the sum of the distinct first-quadrant Gaussian integers dividing n; sequence gives s values.

A078912.name: a(1)=a(2)=1, a(n)=a(n-1)+a(n-2) if n is odd, a(n)=a(n-1)+a(n/2) if n is even.

A078913.name: a(1)=a(2)=1, a(n)=a(n-1)+a(n-2) if n is not congruent to 3, a(n)=a(n-1)+a(n/3) if n is congruent to 3.

A078918.name: a(n) = (a(n-1) + a(n-3)) * a(n-2) / a(n-4). a(1) = a(2) = a(3) = a(4) = 1.
formula: a(n) * a(n-6) = (a(n-1) + a(n-3)) * (a(n-3) + a(n-5)) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 25 2013
a(5-n) = a(n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 25 2013

A078920.name: Upper triangle of Catalan Number Wall.
formula: T(n,k) = Product_{i=1..n-k} Product_{j=i..n-k} (i+j+2*k)/(i+j). [corrected by _Petros Hadjicostas_, Jul 24 2019]

A078922.name: a(n) = 11*a(n-1) - a(n-2) with a(0)=1, a(1) = 10.
formula: a(1)=1, a(2)=10 and for n > 2, a(n) = ceiling(g*f^n) where f = (11+sqrt(117))/2 and g = (1-3/sqrt(13))/2. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jan 12 2003
a(n+1) = ((-1)^n)*S(2*n, i*3), n >= 0, with the imaginary unit i and S(n, x) = U(n, x/2) Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind, A049310.

A078924.name: Array of coefficients of characteristic polynomials of M_n, the n X n matrix with entries m_(i,j) = i mod j.

A078925.name: Triangle of T1(n,m) = number of bracelets (necklaces that can be turned over) with m white beads and (2n+1-m) black ones, for 1<=m<=n.

A078926.name: Number of primitive Pythagorean triangles with perimeter 2n.

A078927.name: Smallest s for which there are exactly n primitive Pythagorean triangles with perimeter 2s; i.e., smallest s such that A078926(s) = n.

A078928.name: Smallest p for which there are exactly n primitive Pythagorean triangles with perimeter p; i.e., smallest p such that A070109(p) = n.

A078930.name: Let r+i*s be the sum of the distinct first-quadrant Gaussian integers dividing n; sequence gives r+s values.

A078931.name: Numbers n such that n divides p(n)+1 or p(n)-1 where p(n) is the n-th prime.

A078932.name: Number of compositions (ordered partitions) of n into powers of 3.
formula: G.f. satisfies A(x) = A(x^3)/(1 - x*A(x^3)), A(0) = 1.

A078933.name: Good examples of Hall's conjecture: integers x such that 0 < |x^3 - y^2| < sqrt(x) for some integer y.

A078934.name: Smallest semiperimeter of integral rectangle with area n*(n+1)/2.

A078935.name: Largest divisor of n*(n+1)/2 that is <= sqrt(n*(n+1)/2).

A078936.name: Smallest divisor of n*(n+1)/2 that is >= sqrt(n*(n+1)/2).

A078937.name: Square of lower triangular matrix of A056857 (successive equalities in set partitions of n).
formula: PE=exp(matpascal(5))/exp(1); A = PE^2; a(n)=A[n,column] with exact integer arithmetic: PE=exp(matpascal(5)-matid(6)); A = PE^2; a(n)=A[n,1] - _Gottfried Helms_, Apr 08 2007
Exponential function of 2*Pascal's triangle (taken as a lower triangular matrix) divided by e^2: [A078937] = (1/e^2)*exp(2*[A007318]) = [A056857]^2.

A078938.name: Cube of lower triangular matrix of A056857 (successive equalities in set partitions of n).
formula: PE=exp(matpascal(5))/exp(1); A = PE^3; a(n)= A[ n,sequentially read ] with exact integer arithmetic: PE=exp(matpascal(5)-matid(6)); A = PE^3; a(n)=A[ n,sequentially read] - _Gottfried Helms_, Apr 08 2007
Exponential function of 3*Pascal's triangle (taken as a lower triangular matrix) divided by e^3: [A078938] = (1/e^3)*exp(3*[A007318]) = [A056857]^3.

A078939.name: Fourth power of lower triangular matrix of A056857 (successive equalities in set partitions of n).
formula: Exponential function of 4*Pascal's triangle (taken as a lower triangular matrix) divided by e^4: [A078939] = (1/e^4)*exp(4*[A007318]) = [A056857]^4.

A078940.name: Row sums of A078938.
formula: Define f_1(x), f_2(x), ... such that f_1(x)=e^x, f_{n+1}(x) = (d/dx)(x*f_n(x)), for n=2,3,.... Then a(n)=e^{-3}*f_n(3). - _Milan Janjic_, May 30 2008
G.f.: 1/T(0), where T(k) = 1 - (k+4)*x - 3*(k+1)*x^2/T(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 15 2016
a(n) = exp(-3) * Sum_{k>=0} (k + 1)^n * 3^k / k!. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 20 2020

A078941.name: Flipping burnt pancakes. Maximum number of spatula flips to sort a stack of n pancakes of different sizes, each burnt on one side, so that the smallest ends up on top, ..., the largest at the bottom and each has its burnt side down.
formula: a(n) >= A078942(n). a(n+1) <= a(n) + 2. 3n/2 <= a(n) <= 2n-2, where the upper bound holds for n>=10.

A078942.name: Flipping burnt pancakes. Given a sorted stack of n burnt pancakes of different sizes (smallest on top, ..., largest at the bottom), each with its burnt side up, a(n) is the number of spatula flips needed to restore them to their initial order but with the burnt sides down.
formula: a(n) <= A078941(n). a(n+1) <= a(n) + 2. 3n/2 <= a(n) <= 47n/30 + c for some constant c.

A078943.name: a(1)=1; a(n+1) is either a(n)-n or a(n)+n, where we choose the smallest one which is a positive integer that's not among the values a(1), ..., a(n).

A078944.name: First column of A078939, the fourth power of lower triangular matrix A056857.
formula: PE=exp(matpascal(5))/exp(1); A = PE^4; a(n)= A[ n,1 ] with exact integer arithmetic: PE=exp(matpascal(5)-matid(6)); A = PE^4; a(n)=A[ n,1]. - _Gottfried Helms_, Apr 08 2007
G.f.: 4*(x/(1-x))*A(x/(1-x)) = A(x) - 1; four times the binomial transform equals this sequence shifted one place left. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Dec 08 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} 4^k*A048993(n, k); A048993: Stirling2 numbers. - _Philippe Deléham_, May 09 2004
G.f.: (G(0) - 1)/(x-1)/4 where G(k) = 1 - 4/(1-k*x)/(1-x/(x-1/G(k+1))); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 16 2013
G.f.: T(0)/(1-4*x), where T(k) = 1 - 4*x^2*(k+1)/(4*x^2*(k+1) - (1-(k+4)*x)*(1-(k+5)*x)/T(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 28 2013
a(n) ~ n^n * exp(n/LambertW(n/4)-4-n) / (sqrt(1+LambertW(n/4)) * LambertW(n/4)^n). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 12 2014
G.f.: Sum_{j>=0} 4^j*x^j / Product_{k=1..j} (1 - k*x). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 07 2019

A078945.name: Row sums of A078939.
formula: Define f_1(x), f_2(x), ... such that f_1(x)=e^x, f_{n+1}(x) = (d/dx)(x*f_n(x)), for n=2,3,.... Then a(n)=e^{-4}*f_n(4). - _Milan Janjic_, May 30 2008

G.f.: T(0)/(1-5*x), where T(k) = 1 - 4*x^2*(k+1)/( 4*x^2*(k+1) - (1-5*x-x*k)*(1-6*x-x*k)/T(k+1) ); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 28 2013

A078978.name: Sequence is S(infinity), where S(1)={1,2,3,4}, S(n+1)=S(n)S'(n) and S'(n) is obtained from S(n) by changing last term using the cyclic permutation 1->2->3->4->1.

A078986.name: Chebyshev T(n,19) polynomial.
formula: a(n) = T(n, 19) = (S(n, 38)-S(n-2, 38))/2 = S(n, 38)-19*S(n-1, 38) with T(n, x), resp. S(n, x), Chebyshev's polynomials of the first, resp. second, kind. See A053120 and A049310. S(n, 38) = A078987(n).
a(n) = (ap^n + am^n)/2 with ap := 19+6*sqrt(10) and am := 19-6*sqrt(10).

A078987.name: Chebyshev U(n,x) polynomial evaluated at x=19.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 38) with S(n, x) = U(n, x/2), Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind. See A049310.

A078988.name: Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = T(2*n+1, sqrt(17))/sqrt(17) = ((-1)^n)*S(2*n, 8*i) = S(n, 66) - S(n-1, 66) with i^2=-1 and T(n, x), resp. S(n, x), Chebyshev's polynomials of the first, resp. second, kind. See A053120 and A049310.
a(n) = 66*a(n-1) - a(n-2) for n>1 ; a(0)=1, a(1)=65. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 18 2008

A078989.name: Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = S(2*n, 2*sqrt(17)) = -i*((-1)^n)*T(2*n+1, 4*i)/4 = S(n, 66) + S(n-1, 66) with i^2=-1 and S(n, x), resp. T(n, x), Chebyshev's polynomials of the second, resp. first, kind. See A049310 and A053120.

A078995.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} C(4*k,k)*C(4*(n-k),n-k).
formula: a(n) = 2/3*(256/27)^n*(1+c/sqrt(n)+o(n^-1/2)) where c = 2/3*sqrt(2/(3*Pi)) = 0.307105910641187... More generally, a(n, m)=sum(k=0, n, binomial(m*k, k)*binomial(m*(n-k), n-k)) is asymptotic to 1/2*m/(m-1)*(m^m/(m-1)^(m-1))^n. See A000302, A006256 for cases m=2 and 3. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jan 26 2003, corrected and extended by _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Nov 06 2012
a(n) = sum(k=0,n,binomial(4*k+l,k)*binomial(4*(n-k)-l,n-k)) for every real number l. - _Rui Duarte_ and António Guedes de Oliveira, Feb 16 2013
